This book explores, for the first time, the links between welfare state provision and teenage reproductive behaviour across a range of countries with differing welfare regimes. Drawing on both welfare state and feminist literature, as well as on new empirical evidence, the book compares public policy responses to teenage parenthood in each 'family' of welfare regime: Nordic, Liberal and Continental (Western European); analyses the different socio-political contexts in which teenage pregnancy is constructed as a social problem and identifies best practice in Europe and the USA. Countries included in the study are the UK, USA, New Zealand, France, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Norway, the Canadian province of Quebec and Russia. The contributors are all internationally recognised experts in the fields of welfare and/or gender studies. When children become parents is important reading for a wide audience of students, policy makers, practitioners and academics in sociology, social policy, social geography, education, psychology, and youth and gender studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aTeenage parentsxGovernment policy. 0aTeenage parents. 0aTeenage pregnancy. 0aWelfare state. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aCharbonneau, Johanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaguerre, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaguerre, Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIvanova, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnudsen, Lisbeth B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuker, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLaughlin, Christine Carter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb